Title_Description: get-azroleassignment uses legacy aad graph api internally  description i found this to be true for both get-azroleassignment and get-azurermroleassignment.   on the back end this commandlet makes several api calls [as documented here]( the first two are against management.azure.com to get role assignments and definitions and then the final one is to get the aad objects returned by the first call.  the issue that i experienced and which ive seen others struggle with is that the third call requires directory.read.all   app   permissions to the   _legacy_   aad graph api when it calls getobjectsbyobjectid. [this page]( shows that the api has been ported to the microsoft graph api (1.0 and beta) as directory/getbyids.  i ran into this issue when trying to enumerate role membership from an azdo release pipeline using a service principal and the powershell commandlets. like [others]( i was seeing microsoft.rest.azure.cloudexception errors when leveraging this command which hid the true issue which was that my service principal wasnt properly authorized to access the aad graph api. i assumed that the commands would be using the ms graph api instead because thats the recommended approach by ms but fiddler showed me the calls to getobjectsbyobjectid. once i saw it was using the   legacy   api i granted app permission to directory.read.all.  i think this command should be updated to use the ms graph api since thats what most people who run into this problem end up doing - writing code to hit the newer rest apis directly instead of trying to figure out why they are experiencing the issue.  i also think itd be worth nothing the permission set required on [the documentation page for get-azroleassignment]( calling out the requirement to make this a delegated permission grant since the call to the graph api isnt 100  obvious when youre thinking about enumerating azure permissions.   steps to reproduce
Name: azure ps team

Title_Description: azurerm = 5.0.0 modules autoloading vs powershell runspaces   description hello ) we are desperate for your help ) a brief description ) we have a custom wrapper/solution to deploy arm templates via new-azurermresourcegroupdeployment powershell cmdlet.  we needed the wrapper as the goal was to use a single vsts azure powershell task to deploy multiple arm templates. the wrapper takes a dictionary of resource groups with corresponding arm templates to deploy into as an input parametes nothing unusual so far. the interesting bit is that the deployments are run in parallel trough a great powershell runspaces wrapper -   each resource group creation and following it new-azurermresourcegroupdeployment are done paralelly each in separate runspace. moreover in each runspace after succesfull deployment a dedicated script is dotsourced and an imported function that uses azurerm modules is called. for the last few months weve been successfully using this solution hundreds if not tousands of times. both from a vsts azure powershell task during release and locally from powershell.  the issue.  up until now weve been running powershell 5 and azurerm module 4.3.1. in that combination everything works fine. also azurerm 4.4.1 works fine. in vsts azure powershell task azurerm and azurerm.profile are imported at the task initialization. all the other modules seem to be autoloaded properly. we do not import anything explicitely in the scripts.  quite recenly we wanted to use azurerm.applicationinsights and invoke-azurermvmruncommand in the release pipeline and decided to update the azurerm module. this is where things got broken. weve tried 5.0.1 5.1.1 and 5.5.0 with the same result. as a rule - only one version of azurerm module is present on the machines. while everything is working fine in the initial powershell session something seems to be working incorrectly in the runspaces. while the functions that get imported via dotsourcing external script from within the runspace are run powerhsell complies that it sees the cmdlets but cant import the proper module...
Name: azure ps team| investigate mag| more info label
